visuals.title: Image based one line drawing
visuals.description:
Another drawing machine, creates an one line drawing based on a given image.

Has two modes: Mode one always looks for the nearest neighbor and connects this two points. Mode two looks up for the 7 nearest neighbors and chooses one of these randomly. Last one makes it look more like a natural drawing.

Controls: 
Mouse click == start over
1-9 == particle number (+start)
I == show / hide image
N == connection mode 
M == straight or curly lines

(Photo is takes by me. It's my small Delorean which decorates my desk)

visuals.title: Summed Area Table
visuals.description:
A Summed Area Table is used to apply a box filter to an image. The benefit of using a SAT is that the processing time is independent of the size of the filter kernel. Move the mouse to change the kernel size. 

The algorithm is entirely stolen from this paper, although any flaws in the implementation are entirely my own:

Crow, Franklin (1984). "Summed-area tables for texture mapping". SIGGRAPH '84: Proceedings of the 11th annual conference on Computer graphics and interactive techniques: 207-212.

visuals.title: Facial Rig
visuals.description:
A more extensive test to get a full blend shape facial rig working online.

I had to write a script in Maya to export poses consistently so that verts would blend without jumping around.

Each control captures 4 different states: Up, down, left, and right. When a control is moved, their deltas all applied to a mesh blending between them all to give the final output.

Good times!
